q3.value: Asking questions through robots during story-reading activities with pre-school children can help engage and inspire children and enhance efficiency in early literacy education.  Although efforts have been made in question dataset collection, our study still face the challenge from the lack of training data in generating educational questions for pre-school children.  This work presents a new dataset for question generation in early literacy education, intended for research on the educational question generation algorithm. The questions collected are supposed to engage and inspire children in conversational story-telling activities.

q4.value: For data collection purpose, our study starts with no hypotheses. However, we do have primary expectation for the quality of collected questions. The questions should have a similar style with the gold-standard questions collected in lab experiments, or at least more similar compared to existing datasets such as SQuAD.

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: Each participate is asked to write 2 questions with answers for each story page. Questions and answers are required in natural language format, so that they can be applied to conversation. To further learn about reasoning behind question answering, participates are required to highlight text in the story context that indicates how answers are derived. For quality check purpose, we decide to collect demographic information about native language and early-education experience.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: Participants will be recruited through Amazon Mechanical Turk platform.  Participants must be from US/Canada region and have a HIT acceptance rate above 97%. This requirement is to control the quality of response based on English stories. Participants will be paid at a rate equivalent to $9 per hour.

q13.value: The target sample size is 100 participants. We will attempt to recruit up to 150, assuming that not all will complete the total task.

q14.value: We will do primarily check using automatic methods to screen participate response. Questions can be the same sentences as in stories. Answers cannot only include pronouns.

q15.value: When there are above 3000 satisfactory question-answer pairs collected, we will terminate the data collection.

Highlighted text indicating answer derivation: as spans

Although we don't set hypothesis for data collection purpose, we plan to run some tests to check data quality and show educational questions' characteristics. We will start a basic analysis for answer type categories, to understand what type of questions and answers are frequently asked in this dataset. If enough parents/teachers join our study, we can analyze the difference between people with or without early-education experience.

q24.value: We expect participates with early-education experience write better educational questions for engaging children in story-telling. We will look for relationships between early-education experience and variables about question quality in terms of cognitive level, such as the percentage of questions requiring  multi-sentence reasoning and types of cognitive ability required by questions.
